Physical Design Implementation Flow

🛠️ Tools & Environment
Synthesis: Cadence Genus
Place & Route: Cadence Innovus
Simulation: Cadence Xcelium

---

 The Flow

✦ Synthesis
Tool: Cadence Genus  
Description: Converts the high-level RTL code into an optimized gate-level netlist. Genus maps the behavioral logic to the target standard cell library while optimizing for Power, Performance, and Area (PPA).

 ✦ Floorplan
Tool: Cadence Innovus  
**Description:** Determines the foundational physical layout of the chip. This involves defining the die size, core area, aspect ratio, strategically placing large hard macros (like SRAMs), and positioning I/O pins to minimize future routing congestion.

 ✦ Powerplan
Tool: Cadence Innovus  
Description: Establishes the power distribution network (PDN). It involves creating VDD and VSS power rings around the core and macros, laying down stripes, and generating rails for the standard cells to ensure uniform power delivery and prevent severe IR drop.

 ✦ Placement
Tool: Cadence Innovus  
Description: Automatically assigns precise physical locations to all standard cells from the netlist within the core area. The placement engine optimizes for timing, reduces overall wirelength, and ensures there are no densely congested areas before the clock tree is built.

✦ Clock Tree Synthesis (CTS)
Tool: Cadence Innovus  
Description: Constructs a balanced, tree-like distribution network for the clock signals. The goal is to route the clock from its root source to all sequential elements (flip-flops) across the chip while minimizing clock skew and maintaining acceptable insertion delay.

 ✦ Routing
Tool: Cadence Innovus  
Description: Performs the actual physical wiring between all placed cells, macros, and pins using the available metal layers and vias. Innovus routes the signal nets to meet final timing constraints while strictly adhering to foundry Design Rule Checks (DRC) and Layout Versus Schematic (LVS) rules.

 ✦ Simulation & Sign-off
Tools: Cadence Xcelium / Tempus / Voltus  
Description: The final verification of the fully routed design. This includes gate-level simulation (Xcelium) to verify logical functionality, Static Timing Analysis (Tempus) for rigorous setup/hold timing sign-off, and power/rail analysis (Voltus) to guarantee chip reliability.
